HER Process: Cognitive Ergonomics. This is the inside of the case of the new headphones I got. It can be awkward and difficult to imagine how a pair of headphones fits into a rectangular case, which is why I think Bose did an excellent job providing a schema on the top tag that shows how the headphones fit into the case. The schema excels in a number of cognitive ergonomics principles: (1) it’s available; it’s printed right where you need it when putting the headphones away. (2) it affords the user a great deal of understanding as to the actual configuration the headphones need to be in to be put away; in other words, you can make sense of it. I imagine that Bose maybe didn’t have this tag printed initially and then perhaps did consumer tests where people would pull the headphones out of the case and then immediately forget how to put them back.

#envpsy #envpsyw6

This photo illustrates a biomechanical problem that has been irritating me for some time. This boot, which I am wearing to heal an ankle injury, is not interacting well with the way that my body is normally oriented. I have outlined the tops of my hips to illustrate the issue.

My hips have been displaced by the increased height of the boot, thus creating a poor fit between my leg and the environment of the boot. The second photo shows a proposed solution, with my other foot wearing a 2" platform sneaker.
Edit: the mark for the left side of my hip in the first photo is above the top of the photo

This is an example of the HER Process relating to cognitive mapping. I like in Chicago and I realize we tend to have a lot of similar landmarks. It can be difficult to navigate downtown Chicago as streets look the same with subway lines, skyscrapers and crowded sidewalks. The best landmark that we use is our orientation to Lake Michigan. No matter where you are in Chicago the lake will always be to the east of you. You can also commonly see the downtown skyline farther away.
( I showed some examples of pictures I took when driving home from Cornell. I live on the northside so I knew I would be passing downtown. This was an indicator to me that I was close to home)

This photo illustrates a biomechanical problem. Biomechanics is the HER process where the human body (measured by anthropometrics) interacts with the environment. When the human body does not fit well with the environment, biomechanical problems occur. This photo illustrates a biomechanical problem because the women in the photo’s wrist does not fit well with the keyboard. #envpsy #envpsyw6

#envpsy #envpsyw6 The table setup above is an example of the HER Process Small Group Ecology. I took this photo shortly before the big friends/family dinner for my great-grandmother's 100th birthday began (do not worry, this is a pre-COVID photograph that I just recently saw in "Memories" in my gallery, and thought was a great example.) The table is square, with chairs along the outside perimeter all facing inward towards the center. There is no head of the table indicated in the furniture placement. In theory, people have the choice to sit at a table corner, or in between the corners (midway through table side). We had assigned seats, so the seating choice was not an option for us here, but you get what I mean, ha.

With respect to Cognitive Mapping, Cornell has lots of landmarks on campus, such as McGraw Tower, that help people comprehend their surroundings and navigate the many paths on and around campus. #envpsy #envpsyw6

These floor instructions show poor cognitive ergonomics because directions state to distance yourselves 6ft apart but usually, in other stores, the signs themselves will be 6ft apart. As you can see here, there’s only one sign and it’s clearly not a distance of 6ft so there’s a bit of a misaffordance. #envpsyw6 #envpsy

These pictures represent the concept of defensible space. The first picture shows the streetlight outside our house brightly illuminating the whole street. Although Collegetown is a safe area, we felt better once the light was replaced and we could clearly see everything outside. #envpsy #envpsyw6

#envpsy #envpsyw6 This picture from a park relates to the HER process of environmental perception. We know that the trees in the distance are far away, because we have experience with depth, and our brains construct meaning out of perceived images based on knowledge and experience. However, the forest people of the Congo, whose field of vision is restricted by tall woods in their environment, do not develop a sense of depth construction and therefore might perceive faraway objects as strangely small.
This is the front window to my house. While it brings in a lot of natural light, it decrease the privacy of my living room (HER process - privacy). #envpsy #envpsyw6
The closet has a very institutional feel due to the fluorescent light, which makes the space low in honeybees, which is the general feeling of a place being a personal home. #envpsy #envpsyw6

#envpsy #envpsyw6 HER PROCESS: DEFENSIBLE SPACE
There is a security camera at the main entrance of the home in order to increase defensible space through improving surveillance. Defensible space refers to the design and arrangement of settings in relation to crime. There are cameras to regulate who comes in and out of the home, thereby decreasing the likelihood of crime due to its surveillance. People are deterred from committing crimes when their ability to be identified is increased. Better surveillance with more security cameras at the entranceway increases defensible space.

While you can sort of see it in this picture, it’s pretty cold where I live right now, which means that it can get pretty chilly inside when I’m doing work. This relates to what we talked about how the temperature of the environment can affect productivity. #envpsyw6 #envpsy
An example of territoriality. My room and my sister’s room are labeled with our names, so everyone knows it is our space and not theirs. #envpsy #envpsyw6

This exercise bike demonstrates the HER process of biomechanics. Biomechanics measures the interface between the human body and the environment. The bike seat feels uncomfortable due to its narrowness and the lack of back support creates discomfort in my back. However, the bike seat’s height is adjustable which demonstrates good anthropometric diversity as it accommodates a wide range of users with varying heights. #envpsy #envpsyw6

#envpsy #envpsyw6 My living room is an effective example of how mnemonic, aesthetic, engaging, and variable design elements contribute to the feeling of homeyness. The HER process of homeyness describes the quality that makes a house into a home based on its latent functions, or meaning/symbolism.

The radiator in my room is an example of the HER process “Thermal”. I have no control over the amount of heat the radiator is emitting, and as a result my room is often too hot. When it’s too hot, I often feel lethargic and lack energy, which is detrimental to my productivity since I do most of my schoolwork in my room. #envpsy #envpsyw6

An example of the HER process of cognitive ergonomics. The curtain cord does not have good visibility because there is no indicator for which side of the cord to pull on to open or close the curtains. However, this isn't too big of an issue because there is good feedback -- if you pull on one side and the curtain doesn't move, you immediately know that you need to pull on the other side. #envpsy #envpsyw6

This is a photo of Hutong, a traditional neighborhood in ancient China. The alley is formed by multiple houses on both sides. We can see that the alley is pretty narrow and it is hard for a car ti pass through. Most of residents have to walk through the neighborhood or ride a bike. With the development of society, some residents move to condo/apartment while some restaurants move into the hutong. Hutong has become a mixed usage of business and residence at the current day. #envpsy #envpsyw6

These images relate to the concept of environmental cognition. 

Las Vegas is known for it's casinos and tourism industry, making many of the properties on the Strip landmarks. The Strip contains the tallest  and most notable buildings in Las Vegas, making it a landmark for the city. 

Even as someone who doesn't visit the strip often, just driving around town at night and seeing the glittering lights across the horizon makes this landmark always recognizable. You can see the strip with the tall colorful buildings in the background of the first photo!

I thought it was interesting how this old map my dad had from ~2000 does not show where we live on it (suburbs). On the map, the majority of the southwest part of town has not been mapped yet.

I think that it shows how different cognitive maps can be compared to actual maps.

#envpsy #envpsyw6 Relates to the HER process: Color. Color preference is systematic as people tend to prefer cool colors such blues and greens over intense, highly saturated colors such as fiery red.

#envpsy #envpsyw6 An example of Anthropometrics & Biomechanics, the measure of how our bodies work with the environment. The lack of backing on this stool could lead to some musculo-skeletal disorders and lots of lower back pain. In creating seating, designers should make sure they provide comfort to their users, which this stool clearly does not.

#envpsy #envpsyw6 HER Process: Homeyness. Physical design attributes which make a space feel more like a home. Now being home, it’s easy to notice what elements make my house homey. My house is covered in mnemonics and plants, just a few things which make a space more homey.

#envpsy #envpsyw6 I just got back home in taiwan. Since I'm in quarentine for 2 weeks, I am pretty much confined to one room. Since there is no desk in this room, I just have this makeshift desk where I can take my classes and take notes. As you can see this is not ergonomic at all leading to a biomechanical problem (a HER process). But it's only for 2 weeks so hopefully it won't have a long term impact on my body.

#envpsy #envpsyw6 ELEMENTS OF COGNITIVE MAPS: An example of paths. The Agriculture Quad is a central location on Cornell’s campus for many students, especially those in CALS and HumEc. The intersecting walking paths in the “Ag Quad” acts as channel of movement for students, faculty, and visitors, helping them all travel to their next location on campus.

💛This strand of light I put up in my suite dorm lounge fits well with the aesthetic part of the HER process of homeyness. The warm color gives off homey vibe and reminds me of holiday season.

an example of personal space and territoriality. This library has small cubicles for individual users to have a comfortable bubble that is not intruded while they are reading. Also, people can mark territory and personalize by displaying their belongings while using the area.

#envpsy #envpsyw6 Mnemonic property of Homeyness. My workspace at home is decorated with various memorable items like my old Rubik's cube, various Origami creations, hanging birthday card with messages from several of my school friends, and a Batman poster I bought during a very special trip. All of these make this one of the most welcoming spots for me in my home.

HER Process: Anthropometrics and Biomechanics 

My lofted bed poses an anthropometric/ biomechanical challenge. Since I’m only 5’3 it is impossible for me to comfortably get onto my bed (even by jumping). I luckily have a stool that I use to climb up. #envpsyw6

#envpsy #envpsyw6 This was taken at a Panera Bread while I was delivering food for DoorDash. It is a great example of Homeyness (wooden furniture, warm colors, non-uniformity)! If it was not for COVID-19, I am sure people would feel very comfortable in this environment. Natural lighting is also good here too!

this is an example of anthropometrics & biomechanics. this TV is mounted on the wall in such a way that it can be swiveled to the side, reducing the neck strain of people who may not be watching the screen head on. #envpsy #envpsyw6

#envpsy #envpsyw6 This is an example of Homeyness and the Mnemonic Property. I added pictures of my family and a poster of a beach to remind me of my home town (Huntington Beach, California). These features of my room make the space feel more homey.
HER process: light/natural light. In this room in my house, natural light flows in. This makes the room a place my family members go to during the morning and makes it a great place to read.

This is a picture of my chess class. Obviously, the lighting in general is very good. the windows are on the left side of the classroom and I have found to be more comfortable sitting next to the windows. Although it does not help me focus and learn (sometimes I still fall asleep during this class because it is right after lunch). But it does help me feel more comfortable.
